I don't know the details of this, but I'll give two examples:

1) private non-profit schools in the US are _required_ to report this
in order to retain their non-profit status.  Being a non-profit is
financially advantageous for the school since then the school
doesn't pay taxes.

2) The formula by which public schools get funded in some states
includes taking into account things like the following:  percent of
low income students,  percent of certain classes of minority
students,  cost of living in the location of the school.

This may or may not be a bad thing (that those things get taken
into account) but it is a true thing!

