school location, say, seem important enough on their own without bringing
ethnicity into it. I mean, the reason why selected minorities are the
targets of affirmative action in the first place is because those ones fare
badly socio-economically as a group. The minorities that don't do badly are
left to get on with it.

I wrote two more paragraphs on the pros and cons of identifying ethnic
groups for the purpose of treating them differently from other groups before
deciding they would contain absolutely no new concepts for people who have
grown up immersed in discussion of the issues of racism and methods for
combating socio-economic disadvantage!

But I do wonder if identifying whole ethnic groups as being disadvantaged
helps or hurts those members of the group who don't fit the stereotypes in
the long run. And does it create additional resentment amongst the various
targeted minority groups when they have to compete for preferment based on
quotas rather than the circumstances of each individual.I can't help feeling
discrimination is perpetuated by a system that carefully identifies its
disadvantaged folk by race rather than the underlying social issues because
while they overlap, they aren't synonymous.

Anyway, I was just struck by the whole concept of thinking about a school's
student population in terms of percentages based on race and what a cultural
disconnect that caused for me. I'll shut up now!

