I agree that it is bizarre.  But let me give you another instance of
why someone might want to do such a thing.  (This may convince you
more and more that public education in the US is going insane - I
won't argue with you on that.)

There is a series of examinations that students need to take.  By
federal law, schools where not enough students pass the exams are
penalized financially, and in other ways.  (Note that _students_ are
not penalized - in fact there are no consequences for the students for
doing badly on these exams, except that their schools get less money.)

Some allowances of various kinds are made for schools that serve
student populations that traditionally do badly on such exams.  One
such population is poor students.  But another such population is
african-american studens who, as a group, perform more poorly on such
exams than &quot;white&quot; students at the same economic level.

(These exams are driving most of public education at this point in the
US, which would be one thing if they were good exams, well thought out
at the national level.  But they are designed state-by-state,
generally poorly tested, often poorly thought out, and as they suck up
more and more resources, are not resulting in any improvements in
school-leavers.)

